ChessTips
// Tips Control the center Develop your pieces early Castle early! Bishops on long diagonals Rooks on open files Connect your rooks Passed pawns must be pushed Knights on the rim are dim Knights are best in the centre Analyse on your opponent\'s turn
// Tip text Start by moving a pawn into the center controlling key squares Getting your pieces out early can help control the center and allows you to be move flexible with your moves, make sure to get your knight out before your bishop Getting your king to safety means that you can start your main plans and attack your opponent without being afraid of getting mated Placing your bishop on the long diagonal lets it control the most possible squares limiting your opponent\'s play Rooks belong on open files they exert the most control here Connected rooks are much more powerful than disconnected ones Pushing passed pawns can put a lot of pressure on your opponent and you get closer to making another queen Knights on the rim are not good as they see very few squares Knights on the 3rd and 4th ranks are excellent defenders while are excellent attackers on the 5th and 6th ranks Think about the position on your opponent\'s turn, how are your pieces positioned?, how is your pawn structure?, Is your king safe?
